4230
4231def values(
4232    values: t.Iterable[t.Tuple[t.Any, ...]],
4233    alias: t.Optional[str] = None,
4234    columns: t.Optional[t.Iterable[str] | t.Dict[str, DataType]] = None,
4235) -> Values:
4236    """Build VALUES statement.
4237
4238    Example:
4239        >>> values([(1, '2')]).sql()
4240        "VALUES (1, '2')"
4241
4242    Args:
4243        values: values statements that will be converted to SQL
4244        alias: optional alias
4245        columns: Optional list of ordered column names or ordered dictionary of column names to types.
4246         If either are provided then an alias is also required.
4247         If a dictionary is provided then the first column of the values will be casted to the expected type
4248         in order to help with type inference.
4249
4250    Returns:
4251        Values: the Values expression object
4252    """
4253    if columns and not alias:
4254        raise ValueError("Alias is required when providing columns")
4255    table_alias = (
4256        TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias), columns=[to_identifier(x) for x in columns])
4257        if columns
4258        else TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias) if alias else None)
4259    )
4260    expressions = [convert(tup) for tup in values]
4261    if columns and isinstance(columns, dict):
4262        types = list(columns.values())
4263        expressions[0].set(
4264            "expressions",
4265            [cast(x, types[i]) for i, x in enumerate(expressions[0].expressions)],
4266        )
4267    return Values(
4268        expressions=expressions,
4269        alias=table_alias,
4270    )
4271
4272
4273def rename_table(old_name: str | Table, new_name: str | Table) -> AlterTable:
4274    """Build ALTER TABLE... RENAME... expression
4275
4276    Args:
4277        old_name: The old name of the table
4278        new_name: The new name of the table
4279
4280    Returns:
4281        Alter table expression
4282    """
4283    old_table = to_table(old_name)
4284    new_table = to_table(new_name)
4285    return AlterTable(
4286        this=old_table,
4287        actions=[
4288            RenameTable(this=new_table),
4289        ],
4290    )

4292
4293def convert(value) -> Expression:
4294    """Convert a python value into an expression object.
4295
4296    Raises an error if a conversion is not possible.
4297
4298    Args:
4299        value (Any): a python object
4300
4301    Returns:
4302        Expression: the equivalent expression object
4303    """
4304    if isinstance(value, Expression):
4305        return value
4306    if value is None:
4307        return NULL
4308    if isinstance(value, bool):
4309        return Boolean(this=value)
4310    if isinstance(value, str):
4311        return Literal.string(value)
4312    if isinstance(value, float) and math.isnan(value):
4313        return NULL
4314    if isinstance(value, numbers.Number):
4315        return Literal.number(value)
4316    if isinstance(value, tuple):
4317        return Tuple(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4318    if isinstance(value, list):
4319        return Array(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4320    if isinstance(value, dict):
4321        return Map(
4322            keys=[convert(k) for k in value],
4323            values=[convert(v) for v in value.values()],
4324        )
4325    if isinstance(value, datetime.datetime):
4326        datetime_literal = Literal.string(
4327            (value if value.tzinfo else value.replace(tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)).isoformat()
4328        )
4329        return TimeStrToTime(this=datetime_literal)
4330    if isinstance(value, datetime.date):
4331        date_literal = Literal.string(value.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))
4332        return DateStrToDate(this=date_literal)
4333    raise ValueError(f"Cannot convert {value}")
4334
4335
4336def replace_children(expression, fun):
4337    """
4338    Replace children of an expression with the result of a lambda fun(child) -> exp.
4339    """
4340    for k, v in expression.args.items():
4341        is_list_arg = isinstance(v, list)
4342
4343        child_nodes = v if is_list_arg else [v]
4344        new_child_nodes = []
4345
4346        for cn in child_nodes:
4347            if isinstance(cn, Expression):
4348                for child_node in ensure_collection(fun(cn)):
4349                    new_child_nodes.append(child_node)
4350                    child_node.parent = expression
4351                    child_node.arg_key = k
4352            else:
4353                new_child_nodes.append(cn)
4354
4355        expression.args[k] = new_child_nodes if is_list_arg else seq_get(new_child_nodes, 0)
4356
4357
4358def column_table_names(expression):
4359    """
4360    Return all table names referenced through columns in an expression.
4361
4362    Example:
4363        >>> import sqlglot
4364        >>> column_table_names(sqlglot.parse_one("a.b AND c.d AND c.e"))
4365        ['c', 'a']
4366
4367    Args:
4368        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression to find table names
4369
4370    Returns:
4371        list: A list of unique names
4372    """
4373    return list(dict.fromkeys(column.table for column in expression.find_all(Column)))
4374
4375
4376def table_name(table) -> str:
4377    """Get the full name of a table as a string.
4378
4379    Args:
4380        table (exp.Table | str): table expression node or string.
4381
4382    Examples:
4383        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4384        >>> table_name(parse_one("select * from a.b.c").find(exp.Table))
4385        'a.b.c'
4386
4387    Returns:
4388        The table name.
4389    """
4390
4391    table = maybe_parse(table, into=Table)
4392
4393    if not table:
4394        raise ValueError(f"Cannot parse {table}")
4395
4396    return ".".join(
4397        part
4398        for part in (
4399            table.text("catalog"),
4400            table.text("db"),
4401            table.name,
4402        )
4403        if part
4404    )
4405
4406
4407def replace_tables(expression, mapping):
4408    """Replace all tables in expression according to the mapping.
4409
4410    Args:
4411        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4412        mapping (Dict[str, str]): mapping of table names.
4413
4414    Examples:
4415        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4416        >>> replace_tables(parse_one("select * from a.b"), {"a.b": "c"}).sql()
4417        'SELECT * FROM c'
4418
4419    Returns:
4420        The mapped expression.
4421    """
4422
4423    def _replace_tables(node):
4424        if isinstance(node, Table):
4425            new_name = mapping.get(table_name(node))
4426            if new_name:
4427                return to_table(
4428                    new_name,
4429                    **{k: v for k, v in node.args.items() if k not in ("this", "db", "catalog")},
4430                )
4431        return node
4432
4433    return expression.transform(_replace_tables)
4434
4435
4436def replace_placeholders(expression, *args, **kwargs):
4437    """Replace placeholders in an expression.
4438
4439    Args:
4440        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4441        args: positional names that will substitute unnamed placeholders in the given order.
4442        kwargs: keyword arguments that will substitute named placeholders.
4443
4444    Examples:
4445        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4446        >>> replace_placeholders(
4447        ...     parse_one("select * from :tbl where ? = ?"), "a", "b", tbl="foo"
4448        ... ).sql()
4449        'SELECT * FROM foo WHERE a = b'
4450
4451    Returns:
4452        The mapped expression.
4453    """
4454
4455    def _replace_placeholders(node, args, **kwargs):
4456        if isinstance(node, Placeholder):
4457            if node.name:
4458                new_name = kwargs.get(node.name)
4459                if new_name:
4460                    return to_identifier(new_name)
4461            else:
4462                try:
4463                    return to_identifier(next(args))
4464                except StopIteration:
4465                    pass
4466        return node
4467
4468    return expression.transform(_replace_placeholders, iter(args), **kwargs)
4469
4470
4471def expand(expression: Expression, sources: t.Dict[str, Subqueryable], copy=True) -> Expression:
4472    """Transforms an expression by expanding all referenced sources into subqueries.
4473
4474    Examples:
4475        >>> from sqlglot import parse_one
4476        >>> expand(parse_one("select * from x AS z"), {"x": parse_one("select * from y")}).sql()
4477        'SELECT * FROM (SELECT * FROM y) AS z /* source: x */'
4478
4479    Args:
4480        expression: The expression to expand.
4481        sources: A dictionary of name to Subqueryables.
4482        copy: Whether or not to copy the expression during transformation. Defaults to True.
4483
4484    Returns:
4485        The transformed expression.
4486    """
4487
4488    def _expand(node: Expression):
4489        if isinstance(node, Table):
4490            name = table_name(node)
4491            source = sources.get(name)
4492            if source:
4493                subquery = source.subquery(node.alias or name)
4494                subquery.comments = [f"source: {name}"]
4495                return subquery
4496        return node
4497
4498    return expression.transform(_expand, copy=copy)
4499
4500
4501def func(name: str, *args, dialect: DialectType = None, **kwargs) -> Func:
4502    """
4503    Returns a Func expression.
4504
4505    Examples:
4506        >>> func("abs", 5).sql()
4507        'ABS(5)'
4508
4509        >>> func("cast", this=5, to=DataType.build("DOUBLE")).sql()
4510        'CAST(5 AS DOUBLE)'
4511
4512    Args:
4513        name: the name of the function to build.
4514        args: the args used to instantiate the function of interest.
4515        dialect: the source dialect.
4516        kwargs: the kwargs used to instantiate the function of interest.
4517
4518    Note:
4519        The arguments `args` and `kwargs` are mutually exclusive.
4520
4521    Returns:
4522        An instance of the function of interest, or an anonymous function, if `name` doesn't
4523        correspond to an existing `sqlglot.expressions.Func` class.
4524    """
4525    if args and kwargs:
4526        raise ValueError("Can't use both args and kwargs to instantiate a function.")
4527
4528    from sqlglot.dialects.dialect import Dialect
4529
4530    args = tuple(convert(arg) for arg in args)
4531    kwargs = {key: convert(value) for key, value in kwargs.items()}
4532
4533    parser = Dialect.get_or_raise(dialect)().parser()
4534    from_args_list = parser.FUNCTIONS.get(name.upper())
4535
4536    if from_args_list:
4537        function = from_args_list(args) if args else from_args_list.__self__(**kwargs)  # type: ignore
4538    else:
4539        kwargs = kwargs or {"expressions": args}
4540        function = Anonymous(this=name, **kwargs)
4541
4542    for error_message in function.error_messages(args):
4543        raise ValueError(error_message)
4544
4545    return function
4546

4550    Returns a true Boolean expression.
4551    """
4552    return Boolean(this=True)

4554
4555def false():
4556    """
4557    Returns a false Boolean expression.
4558    """
4559    return Boolean(this=False)

4562def null():
4563    """
4564    Returns a Null expression.
4565    """
4566    return Null()
4567
4568
4569# TODO: deprecate this
4570TRUE = Boolean(this=True)
4571FALSE = Boolean(this=False)
4572NULL = Null()
class Expression: 
 54class Expression(metaclass=_Expression):
 55    """
 56    The base class for all expressions in a syntax tree. Each Expression encapsulates any necessary
 57    context, such as its child expressions, their names (arg keys), and whether a given child expression
 58    is optional or not.
 59
 60    Attributes:
 61        key: a unique key for each class in the Expression hierarchy. This is useful for hashing
 62            and representing expressions as strings.
 63        arg_types: determines what arguments (child nodes) are supported by an expression. It
 64            maps arg keys to booleans that indicate whether the corresponding args are optional.
 65
 66    Example:
 67        >>> class Foo(Expression):
 68        ...     arg_types = {"this": True, "expression": False}
 69
 70        The above definition informs us that Foo is an Expression that requires an argument called
 71        "this" and may also optionally receive an argument called "expression".
 72
 73    Args:
 74        args: a mapping used for retrieving the arguments of an expression, given their arg keys.
 75        parent: a reference to the parent expression (or None, in case of root expressions).
 76        arg_key: the arg key an expression is associated with, i.e. the name its parent expression
 77            uses to refer to it.
 78        comments: a list of comments that are associated with a given expression. This is used in
 79            order to preserve comments when transpiling SQL code.
 80        _type: the `sqlglot.expressions.DataType` type of an expression. This is inferred by the
 81            optimizer, in order to enable some transformations that require type information.
 82    """
 83
 84    key = "expression"
 85    arg_types = {"this": True}
 86    __slots__ = ("args", "parent", "arg_key", "comments", "_type")
 87
 88    def __init__(self, **args: t.Any):
 89        self.args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = args
 90        self.parent: t.Optional[Expression] = None
 91        self.arg_key: t.Optional[str] = None
 92        self.comments: t.Optional[t.List[str]] = None
 93        self._type: t.Optional[DataType] = None
 94
 95        for arg_key, value in self.args.items():
 96            self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
 97
 98    def __eq__(self, other) -> bool:
 99        return type(self) is type(other) and _norm_args(self) == _norm_args(other)
100
101    def __hash__(self) -> int:
102        return hash(
103            (
104                self.key,
105                tuple(
106                    (k, tuple(v) if isinstance(v, list) else v) for k, v in _norm_args(self).items()
107                ),
108            )
109        )
110
111    @property
112    def this(self):
113        """
114        Retrieves the argument with key "this".
115        """
116        return self.args.get("this")
117
118    @property
119    def expression(self):
120        """
121        Retrieves the argument with key "expression".
122        """
123        return self.args.get("expression")
124
125    @property
126    def expressions(self):
127        """
128        Retrieves the argument with key "expressions".
129        """
130        return self.args.get("expressions") or []
131
132    def text(self, key):
133        """
134        Returns a textual representation of the argument corresponding to "key". This can only be used
135        for args that are strings or leaf Expression instances, such as identifiers and literals.
136        """
137        field = self.args.get(key)
138        if isinstance(field, str):
139            return field
140        if isinstance(field, (Identifier, Literal, Var)):
141            return field.this
142        return ""
143
144    @property
145    def is_string(self):
146        """
147        Checks whether a Literal expression is a string.
148        """
149        return isinstance(self, Literal) and self.args["is_string"]
150
151    @property
152    def is_number(self):
153        """
154        Checks whether a Literal expression is a number.
155        """
156        return isinstance(self, Literal) and not self.args["is_string"]
157
158    @property
159    def is_int(self):
160        """
161        Checks whether a Literal expression is an integer.
162        """
163        if self.is_number:
164            try:
165                int(self.name)
166                return True
167            except ValueError:
168                pass
169        return False
170
171    @property
172    def alias(self):
173        """
174        Returns the alias of the expression, or an empty string if it's not aliased.
175        """
176        if isinstance(self.args.get("alias"), TableAlias):
177            return self.args["alias"].name
178        return self.text("alias")
179
180    @property
181    def name(self):
182        return self.text("this")
183
184    @property
185    def alias_or_name(self):
186        if isinstance(self, Null):
187            return "NULL"
188        return self.alias or self.name
189
190    @property
191    def output_name(self):
192        """
193        Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.
194
195        If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.
196
197        Example:
198            >>> from sqlglot import parse_one
199            >>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
200            'a'
201            >>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
202            'c'
203            >>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
204            ''
205        """
206        return ""
207
208    @property
209    def type(self) -> t.Optional[DataType]:
210        return self._type
211
212    @type.setter
213    def type(self, dtype: t.Optional[DataType | DataType.Type | str]) -> None:
214        if dtype and not isinstance(dtype, DataType):
215            dtype = DataType.build(dtype)
216        self._type = dtype  # type: ignore
217
218    def __deepcopy__(self, memo):
219        copy = self.__class__(**deepcopy(self.args))
220        copy.comments = self.comments
221        copy.type = self.type
222        return copy
223
224    def copy(self):
225        """
226        Returns a deep copy of the expression.
227        """
228        new = deepcopy(self)
229        new.parent = self.parent
230        for item, parent, _ in new.bfs():
231            if isinstance(item, Expression) and parent:
232                item.parent = parent
233        return new
234
235    def append(self, arg_key, value):
236        """
237        Appends value to arg_key if it's a list or sets it as a new list.
238
239        Args:
240            arg_key (str): name of the list expression arg
241            value (Any): value to append to the list
242        """
243        if not isinstance(self.args.get(arg_key), list):
244            self.args[arg_key] = []
245        self.args[arg_key].append(value)
246        self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
247
248    def set(self, arg_key, value):
249        """
250        Sets `arg_key` to `value`.
251
252        Args:
253            arg_key (str): name of the expression arg.
254            value: value to set the arg to.
255        """
256        self.args[arg_key] = value
257        self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
258
259    def _set_parent(self, arg_key, value):
260        if isinstance(value, Expression):
261            value.parent = self
262            value.arg_key = arg_key
263        elif isinstance(value, list):
264            for v in value:
265                if isinstance(v, Expression):
266                    v.parent = self
267                    v.arg_key = arg_key
268
269    @property
270    def depth(self):
271        """
272        Returns the depth of this tree.
273        """
274        if self.parent:
275            return self.parent.depth + 1
276        return 0
277
278    def find(self, *expression_types, bfs=True):
279        """
280        Returns the first node in this tree which matches at least one of
281        the specified types.
282
283        Args:
284            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
285
286        Returns:
287            The node which matches the criteria or None if no such node was found.
288        """
289        return next(self.find_all(*expression_types, bfs=bfs), None)
290
291    def find_all(self, *expression_types, bfs=True):
292        """
293        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree and only
294        yields those that match at least one of the specified expression types.
295
296        Args:
297            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
298
299        Returns:
300            The generator object.
301        """
302        for expression, _, _ in self.walk(bfs=bfs):
303            if isinstance(expression, expression_types):
304                yield expression
305
306    def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types):
307        """
308        Returns a nearest parent matching expression_types.
309
310        Args:
311            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
312
313        Returns:
314            The parent node.
315        """
316        ancestor = self.parent
317        while ancestor and not isinstance(ancestor, expression_types):
318            ancestor = ancestor.parent
319        return ancestor
320
321    @property
322    def parent_select(self):
323        """
324        Returns the parent select statement.
325        """
326        return self.find_ancestor(Select)
327
328    def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None):
329        """
330        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.
331
332        Args:
333            bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied,
334                otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
335            prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if
336                the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
337
338        Returns:
339            the generator object.
340        """
341        if bfs:
342            yield from self.bfs(prune=prune)
343        else:
344            yield from self.dfs(prune=prune)
345
346    def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None):
347        """
348        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
349        the DFS (Depth-first) order.
350
351        Returns:
352            The generator object.
353        """
354        parent = parent or self.parent
355        yield self, parent, key
356        if prune and prune(self, parent, key):
357            return
358
359        for k, v in self.args.items():
360            for node in ensure_collection(v):
361                if isinstance(node, Expression):
362                    yield from node.dfs(self, k, prune)
363
364    def bfs(self, prune=None):
365        """
366        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
367        the BFS (Breadth-first) order.
368
369        Returns:
370            The generator object.
371        """
372        queue = deque([(self, self.parent, None)])
373
374        while queue:
375            item, parent, key = queue.popleft()
376
377            yield item, parent, key
378            if prune and prune(item, parent, key):
379                continue
380
381            if isinstance(item, Expression):
382                for k, v in item.args.items():
383                    for node in ensure_collection(v):
384                        if isinstance(node, Expression):
385                            queue.append((node, item, k))
386
387    def unnest(self):
388        """
389        Returns the first non parenthesis child or self.
390        """
391        expression = self
392        while isinstance(expression, Paren):
393            expression = expression.this
394        return expression
395
396    def unalias(self):
397        """
398        Returns the inner expression if this is an Alias.
399        """
400        if isinstance(self, Alias):
401            return self.this
402        return self
403
404    def unnest_operands(self):
405        """
406        Returns unnested operands as a tuple.
407        """
408        return tuple(arg.unnest() for arg in self.args.values() if arg)
409
410    def flatten(self, unnest=True):
411        """
412        Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.
413
414        A AND B AND C -> [A, B, C]
415        """
416        for node, _, _ in self.dfs(prune=lambda n, p, *_: p and not isinstance(n, self.__class__)):
417            if not isinstance(node, self.__class__):
418                yield node.unnest() if unnest else node
419
420    def __str__(self):
421        return self.sql()
422
423    def __repr__(self):
424        return self._to_s()
425
426    def sql(self, dialect: DialectType = None, **opts) -> str:
427        """
428        Returns SQL string representation of this tree.
429
430        Args:
431            dialect: the dialect of the output SQL string (eg. "spark", "hive", "presto", "mysql").
432            opts: other `sqlglot.generator.Generator` options.
433
434        Returns:
435            The SQL string.
436        """
437        from sqlglot.dialects import Dialect
438
439        return Dialect.get_or_raise(dialect)().generate(self, **opts)
440
441    def _to_s(self, hide_missing: bool = True, level: int = 0) -> str:
442        indent = "" if not level else "\n"
443        indent += "".join(["  "] * level)
444        left = f"({self.key.upper()} "
445
446        args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = {
447            k: ", ".join(
448                v._to_s(hide_missing=hide_missing, level=level + 1)
449                if hasattr(v, "_to_s")
450                else str(v)
451                for v in ensure_collection(vs)
452                if v is not None
453            )
454            for k, vs in self.args.items()
455        }
456        args["comments"] = self.comments
457        args["type"] = self.type
458        args = {k: v for k, v in args.items() if v or not hide_missing}
459
460        right = ", ".join(f"{k}: {v}" for k, v in args.items())
461        right += ")"
462
463        return indent + left + right
464
465    def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs):
466        """
467        Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones)
468        and applies the given transformation function to each node.
469
470        Args:
471            fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a
472                new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function
473                returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
474            copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is
475                modified in place.
476
477        Returns:
478            The transformed tree.
479        """
480        node = self.copy() if copy else self
481        new_node = fun(node, *args, **kwargs)
482
483        if new_node is None or not isinstance(new_node, Expression):
484            return new_node
485        if new_node is not node:
486            new_node.parent = node.parent
487            return new_node
488
489        replace_children(new_node, lambda child: child.transform(fun, *args, copy=False, **kwargs))
490        return new_node
491
492    def replace(self, expression):
493        """
494        Swap out this expression with a new expression.
495
496        For example::
497
498            >>> tree = Select().select("x").from_("tbl")
499            >>> tree.find(Column).replace(Column(this="y"))
500            (COLUMN this: y)
501            >>> tree.sql()
502            'SELECT y FROM tbl'
503
504        Args:
505            expression (Expression|None): new node
506
507        Returns:
508            The new expression or expressions.
509        """
510        if not self.parent:
511            return expression
512
513        parent = self.parent
514        self.parent = None
515
516        replace_children(parent, lambda child: expression if child is self else child)
517        return expression
518
519    def pop(self):
520        """
521        Remove this expression from its AST.
522        """
523        self.replace(None)
524
525    def assert_is(self, type_):
526        """
527        Assert that this `Expression` is an instance of `type_`.
528
529        If it is NOT an instance of `type_`, this raises an assertion error.
530        Otherwise, this returns this expression.
531
532        Examples:
533            This is useful for type security in chained expressions:
534
535            >>> import sqlglot
536            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT x from y").assert_is(Select).select("z").sql()
537            'SELECT x, z FROM y'
538        """
539        assert isinstance(self, type_)
540        return self
541
542    def error_messages(self, args: t.Optional[t.Sequence] = None) -> t.List[str]:
543        """
544        Checks if this expression is valid (e.g. all mandatory args are set).
545
546        Args:
547            args: a sequence of values that were used to instantiate a Func expression. This is used
548                to check that the provided arguments don't exceed the function argument limit.
549
550        Returns:
551            A list of error messages for all possible errors that were found.
552        """
553        errors: t.List[str] = []
554
555        for k in self.args:
556            if k not in self.arg_types:
557                errors.append(f"Unexpected keyword: '{k}' for {self.__class__}")
558        for k, mandatory in self.arg_types.items():
559            v = self.args.get(k)
560            if mandatory and (v is None or (isinstance(v, list) and not v)):
561                errors.append(f"Required keyword: '{k}' missing for {self.__class__}")
562
563        if (
564            args
565            and isinstance(self, Func)
566            and len(args) > len(self.arg_types)
567            and not self.is_var_len_args
568        ):
569            errors.append(
570                f"The number of provided arguments ({len(args)}) is greater than "
571                f"the maximum number of supported arguments ({len(self.arg_types)})"
572            )
573
574        return errors
575
576    def dump(self):
577        """
578        Dump this Expression to a JSON-serializable dict.
579        """
580        from sqlglot.serde import dump
581
582        return dump(self)
583
584    @classmethod
585    def load(cls, obj):
586        """
587        Load a dict (as returned by `Expression.dump`) into an Expression instance.
588        """
589        from sqlglot.serde import load
590
591        return load(obj)

The base class for all expressions in a syntax tree. Each Expression encapsulates any necessary context, such as its child expressions, their names (arg keys), and whether a given child expression is optional or not.

Attributes
  • key: a unique key for each class in the Expression hierarchy. This is useful for hashing and representing expressions as strings.
  • arg_types: determines what arguments (child nodes) are supported by an expression. It maps arg keys to booleans that indicate whether the corresponding args are optional.
Example
>>> class Foo(Expression):
...     arg_types = {"this": True, "expression": False}

The above definition informs us that Foo is an Expression that requires an argument called "this" and may also optionally receive an argument called "expression".

Args
  • args: a mapping used for retrieving the arguments of an expression, given their arg keys.
  • parent: a reference to the parent expression (or None, in case of root expressions).
  • arg_key: the arg key an expression is associated with, i.e. the name its parent expression uses to refer to it.
  • comments: a list of comments that are associated with a given expression. This is used in order to preserve comments when transpiling SQL code.
  • _type: the sqlglot.expressions.DataType type of an expression. This is inferred by the optimizer, in order to enable some transformations that require type information.
Expression(**args: Any) 
88    def __init__(self, **args: t.Any):
89        self.args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = args
90        self.parent: t.Optional[Expression] = None
91        self.arg_key: t.Optional[str] = None
92        self.comments: t.Optional[t.List[str]] = None

def text(self, key): 
132    def text(self, key):
133        """
134        Returns a textual representation of the argument corresponding to "key". This can only be used
135        for args that are strings or leaf Expression instances, such as identifiers and literals.
136        """
137        field = self.args.get(key)
138        if isinstance(field, str):
139            return field
140        if isinstance(field, (Identifier, Literal, Var)):
141            return field.this
142        return ""

def copy(self): 
224    def copy(self):
225        """
226        Returns a deep copy of the expression.
227        """
228        new = deepcopy(self)
229        new.parent = self.parent
230        for item, parent, _ in new.bfs():
231            if isinstance(item, Expression) and parent:
232                item.parent = parent
233        return new

Returns a deep copy of the expression.

def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types): 
306    def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types):
307        """
308        Returns a nearest parent matching expression_types.
309

311            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
312
313        Returns:
314            The parent node.
315        """
316        ancestor = self.parent
317        while ancestor and not isinstance(ancestor, expression_types):
318            ancestor = ancestor.parent
319        return ancestor

def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None): 
328    def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None):
329        """
330        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.
331
332        Args:
333            bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied,
334                otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
335            prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if
336                the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
337
338        Returns:
339            the generator object.
340        """
341        if bfs:
342            yield from self.bfs(prune=prune)
343        else:
344            yield from self.dfs(prune=prune)

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.

Args
  • bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied, otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
  • prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
Returns

the generator object.

def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None): 
346    def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None):
347        """
348        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
349        the DFS (Depth-first) order.
350
351        Returns:
352            The generator object.
353        """
354        parent = parent or self.parent
355        yield self, parent, key
356        if prune and prune(self, parent, key):
357            return
358
359        for k, v in self.args.items():
360            for node in ensure_collection(v):
361                if isinstance(node, Expression):
362                    yield from node.dfs(self, k, prune)

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in the DFS (Depth-first) order.

Returns

The generator object.

def bfs(self, prune=None): 
364    def bfs(self, prune=None):
365        """
366        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
367        the BFS (Breadth-first) order.
368
369        Returns:
370            The generator object.
371        """
372        queue = deque([(self, self.parent, None)])
373
374        while queue:
375            item, parent, key = queue.popleft()
376
377            yield item, parent, key
378            if prune and prune(item, parent, key):
379                continue
380
381            if isinstance(item, Expression):
382                for k, v in item.args.items():
383                    for node in ensure_collection(v):
384                        if isinstance(node, Expression):
385                            queue.append((node, item, k))

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in the BFS (Breadth-first) order.

Returns

The generator object.

def flatten(self, unnest=True): 
410    def flatten(self, unnest=True):
411        """
412        Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.
413
414        A AND B AND C -> [A, B, C]
415        """
416        for node, _, _ in self.dfs(prune=lambda n, p, *_: p and not isinstance(n, self.__class__)):
417            if not isinstance(node, self.__class__):
418                yield node.unnest() if unnest else node

Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.

def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs): 
465    def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs):
466        """
467        Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones)
468        and applies the given transformation function to each node.
469
470        Args:
471            fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a
472                new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function
473                returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
474            copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is
475                modified in place.
476
477        Returns:
478            The transformed tree.
479        """
480        node = self.copy() if copy else self
481        new_node = fun(node, *args, **kwargs)
482
483        if new_node is None or not isinstance(new_node, Expression):
484            return new_node
485        if new_node is not node:
486            new_node.parent = node.parent
487            return new_node
488
489        replace_children(new_node, lambda child: child.transform(fun, *args, copy=False, **kwargs))
490        return new_node

Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones) and applies the given transformation function to each node.

Args
  • fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
  • copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is modified in place.
Returns

The transformed tree.

def replace(self, expression): 
492    def replace(self, expression):
493        """
494        Swap out this expression with a new expression.
495
496        For example::
497
498            >>> tree = Select().select("x").from_("tbl")
499            >>> tree.find(Column).replace(Column(this="y"))
500            (COLUMN this: y)
501            >>> tree.sql()
502            'SELECT y FROM tbl'
503
504        Args:
505            expression (Expression|None): new node
506
507        Returns:
508            The new expression or expressions.
509        """
510        if not self.parent:
511            return expression
512
513        parent = self.parent
514        self.parent = None
515
516        replace_children(parent, lambda child: expression if child is self else child)
517        return expression

Swap out this expression with a new expression.

For example::

>>> tree = Select().select("x").from_("tbl")
>>> tree.find(Column).replace(Column(this="y"))
(COLUMN this: y)
>>> tree.sql()
'SELECT y FROM tbl'
Args
  • expression (Expression|None): new node
Returns

The new expression or expressions.

def assert_is(self, type_): 
525    def assert_is(self, type_):
526        """
527        Assert that this `Expression` is an instance of `type_`.
528
529        If it is NOT an instance of `type_`, this raises an assertion error.
530        Otherwise, this returns this expression.
531
532        Examples:
533            This is useful for type security in chained expressions:
534
535            >>> import sqlglot
536            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT x from y").assert_is(Select).select("z").sql()
537            'SELECT x, z FROM y'
538        """
539        assert isinstance(self, type_)
540        return self

Assert that this Expression is an instance of type_.

def error_messages(self, args: Optional[Sequence] = None) -> List[str]: 
542    def error_messages(self, args: t.Optional[t.Sequence] = None) -> t.List[str]:
543        """
544        Checks if this expression is valid (e.g. all mandatory args are set).
545
546        Args:
547            args: a sequence of values that were used to instantiate a Func expression. This is used
548                to check that the provided arguments don't exceed the function argument limit.
549
550        Returns:
551            A list of error messages for all possible errors that were found.
552        """
553        errors: t.List[str] = []
554
555        for k in self.args:
556            if k not in self.arg_types:
557                errors.append(f"Unexpected keyword: '{k}' for {self.__class__}")
558        for k, mandatory in self.arg_types.items():
559            v = self.args.get(k)
560            if mandatory and (v is None or (isinstance(v, list) and not v)):
561                errors.append(f"Required keyword: '{k}' missing for {self.__class__}")
562
563        if (
564            args
565            and isinstance(self, Func)
566            and len(args) > len(self.arg_types)
567            and not self.is_var_len_args
568        ):
569            errors.append(
570                f"The number of provided arguments ({len(args)}) is greater than "
571                f"the maximum number of supported arguments ({len(self.arg_types)})"
572            )
573
574        return errors

Checks if this expression is valid (e.g. all mandatory args are set).

Args
  • args: a sequence of values that were used to instantiate a Func expression. This is used to check that the provided arguments don't exceed the function argument limit.
Returns

A list of error messages for all possible errors that were found.

class DerivedTable(Expression): 
659class DerivedTable(Expression):
660    @property
661    def alias_column_names(self):
662        table_alias = self.args.get("alias")
663        if not table_alias:
664            return []
665        column_list = table_alias.assert_is(TableAlias).args.get("columns") or []
666        return [c.name for c in column_list]
667
668    @property
669    def selects(self):
670        alias = self.args.get("alias")
671
672        if alias:
673            return alias.columns
674        return []

677    def named_selects(self):
678        return [select.output_name for select in self.selects]

681class Unionable(Expression):
682    def union(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
683        """
684        Builds a UNION expression.
685
686        Example:
687            >>> import sqlglot
688            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").union("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
689            'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
690
691        Args:
692            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string.
693                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
694            distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
695            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
696            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
697        Returns:
698            Union: the Union expression.
699        """
700        return union(left=self, right=expression, distinct=distinct, dialect=dialect, **opts)
701

>>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").union("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
Args
  • expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns

Union: the Union expression.

def intersect(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts): 
702    def intersect(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
703        """
704        Builds an INTERSECT expression.
705
706        Example:
707            >>> import sqlglot
708            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").intersect("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
709            'SELECT * FROM foo INTERSECT SELECT * FROM bla'
710
711        Args:
712            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string.
713                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
714            distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
715            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
716            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
717        Returns:
718            Intersect: the Intersect expression
719        """
720        return intersect(left=self, right=expression, distinct=distinct, dialect=dialect, **opts)

class Column(Condition): 
874class Column(Condition):
875    arg_types = {"this": True, "table": False}
876
877    @property
878    def table(self):
879        return self.text("table")
880
881    @property
882    def output_name(self):
883        return self.name
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

1166    def on(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts):
1167        """
1168        Append to or set the ON expressions.
1169
1170        Example:
1171            >>> import sqlglot
1172            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("JOIN x", into=Join).on("y = 1").sql()
1173            'JOIN x ON y = 1'
1174
1175        Args:
1176            *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
1177                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
1178                Multiple expressions are combined with an AND operator.
1179            append (bool): if `True`, AND the new expressions to any existing expression.
1180                Otherwise, this resets the expression.
1181            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
1182            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1183            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1184
1185        Returns:
1186            Join: the modified join expression.
1187        """
1188        join = _apply_conjunction_builder(
1189            *expressions,
1190            instance=self,
1191            arg="on",
1192            append=append,
1193            dialect=dialect,
1194            copy=copy,
1195            **opts,
1196        )
1197
1198        if join.kind == "CROSS":
1199            join.set("kind", None)
1200
1201        return join
1202
1203    def using(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts):
1204        """
1205        Append to or set the USING expressions.
1206
1207        Example:
1208            >>> import sqlglot
1209            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("JOIN x", into=Join).using("foo", "bla").sql()

1211
1212        Args:
1213            *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
1214                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
1215            append (bool): if `True`, concatenate the new expressions to the existing "using" list.
1216                Otherwise, this resets the expression.
1217            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
1218            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1219            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1220
1221        Returns:
1222            Join: the modified join expression.
1223        """
1224        join = _apply_list_builder(
1225            *expressions,
1226            instance=self,
1227            arg="using",
1228            append=append,
1229            dialect=dialect,
1230            copy=copy,
1231            **opts,
1232        )
1233
1234        if join.kind == "CROSS":
1235            join.set("kind", None)

class Properties(Expression): 
1443class Properties(Expression):
1444    arg_types = {"expressions": True}
1445
1446    NAME_TO_PROPERTY = {
1447        "ALGORITHM": AlgorithmProperty,
1448        "AUTO_INCREMENT": AutoIncrementProperty,
1449        "CHARACTER SET": CharacterSetProperty,
1450        "COLLATE": CollateProperty,
1451        "COMMENT": SchemaCommentProperty,
1452        "DEFINER": DefinerProperty,
1453        "DISTKEY": DistKeyProperty,
1454        "DISTSTYLE": DistStyleProperty,
1455        "ENGINE": EngineProperty,
1456        "EXECUTE AS": ExecuteAsProperty,
1457        "FORMAT": FileFormatProperty,
1458        "LANGUAGE": LanguageProperty,
1459        "LOCATION": LocationProperty,
1460        "PARTITIONED_BY": PartitionedByProperty,
1461        "RETURNS": ReturnsProperty,
1462        "SORTKEY": SortKeyProperty,
1463        "TABLE_FORMAT": TableFormatProperty,
1464    }
1465
1466    PROPERTY_TO_NAME = {v: k for k, v in NAME_TO_PROPERTY.items()}
1467
1468    class Location(AutoName):
1469        POST_CREATE = auto()
1470        PRE_SCHEMA = auto()
1471        POST_INDEX = auto()
1472        POST_SCHEMA_ROOT = auto()
1473        POST_SCHEMA_WITH = auto()
1474        UNSUPPORTED = auto()
1475
1476    @classmethod
1477    def from_dict(cls, properties_dict) -> Properties:
1478        expressions = []
1479        for key, value in properties_dict.items():
1480            property_cls = cls.NAME_TO_PROPERTY.get(key.upper())
1481            if property_cls:
1482                expressions.append(property_cls(this=convert(value)))
1483            else:
1484                expressions.append(Property(this=Literal.string(key), value=convert(value)))
1485
1486        return cls(expressions=expressions)
@classmethod
def from_dict(cls, properties_dict) -> sqlglot.expressions.Properties: 
1476    @classmethod
1477    def from_dict(cls, properties_dict) -> Properties:
1478        expressions = []
1479        for key, value in properties_dict.items():
1480            property_cls = cls.NAME_TO_PROPERTY.get(key.upper())
1481            if property_cls:
1482                expressions.append(property_cls(this=convert(value)))
1483            else:
1484                expressions.append(Property(this=Literal.string(key), value=convert(value)))
1485
1486        return cls(expressions=expressions)

class Subqueryable(Unionable): 
1506class Subqueryable(Unionable):
1507    def subquery(self, alias=None, copy=True) -> Subquery:
1508        """
1509        Convert this expression to an aliased expression that can be used as a Subquery.
1510
1511        Example:
1512            >>> subquery = Select().select("x").from_("tbl").subquery()
1513            >>> Select().select("x").from_(subquery).sql()
1514            'SELECT x FROM (SELECT x FROM tbl)'
1515
1516        Args:
1517            alias (str | Identifier): an optional alias for the subquery
1518            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1519
1520        Returns:
1521            Alias: the subquery
1522        """
1523        instance = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
1524        return Subquery(
1525            this=instance,
1526            alias=TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias)),
1527        )
1528
1529    def limit(self, expression, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:
1530        raise NotImplementedError
1531
1532    @property
1533    def ctes(self):
1534        with_ = self.args.get("with")
1535        if not with_:
1536            return []
1537        return with_.expressions
1538
1539    @property
1540    def selects(self):
1541        raise NotImplementedError("Subqueryable objects must implement `selects`")
1542
1543    @property
1544    def named_selects(self):
1545        raise NotImplementedError("Subqueryable objects must implement `named_selects`")
1546
1547    def with_(
1548        self,
1549        alias,
1550        as_,
1551        recursive=None,
1552        append=True,
1553        dialect=None,
1554        copy=True,
1555        **opts,
1556    ):
1557        """
1558        Append to or set the common table expressions.
1559
1560        Example:
1561            >>> Select().with_("tbl2", as_="SELECT * FROM tbl").select("x").from_("tbl2").sql()
1562            'WITH tbl2 AS (SELECT * FROM tbl) SELECT x FROM tbl2'
1563
1564        Args:
1565            alias (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table name.
1566                If an `Expression` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1567            as_ (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table expression.
1568                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
1569            recursive (bool): set the RECURSIVE part of the expression. Defaults to `False`.
1570            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
1571                Otherwise, this resets the expressions.
1572            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1573            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1574            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1575
1576        Returns:
1577            Select: the modified expression.
1578        """
1579        alias_expression = maybe_parse(
1580            alias,
1581            dialect=dialect,
1582            into=TableAlias,
1583            **opts,
1584        )
1585        as_expression = maybe_parse(
1586            as_,
1587            dialect=dialect,
1588            **opts,
1589        )
1590        cte = CTE(
1591            this=as_expression,
1592            alias=alias_expression,
1593        )
1594        return _apply_child_list_builder(
1595            cte,
1596            instance=self,
1597            arg="with",
1598            append=append,
1599            copy=copy,
1600            into=With,
1601            properties={"recursive": recursive or False},
1602        )

1658        """
1659        Set the LIMIT expression.
1660
1661        Example:
1662            >>> select("1").union(select("1")).limit(1).sql()
1663            'SELECT * FROM (SELECT 1 UNION SELECT 1) AS _l_0 LIMIT 1'
1664

1667                This can also be an integer.

1678            select("*")

1680            .limit(expression, dialect=dialect, copy=False, **opts)
1681        )

class Select(Subqueryable): 
1749class Select(Subqueryable):
1750    arg_types = {

1760    def from_(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:
1761        """
1762        Set the FROM expression.
1763
1764        Example:
1765            >>> Select().from_("tbl").select("x").sql()
1766            'SELECT x FROM tbl'
1767
1768        Args:
1769            *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
1770                If a `From` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1771                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be wrapped in a `From`.
1772            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
1773                Otherwise, this flattens all the `From` expression into a single expression.
1774            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1775            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1776            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1777
1778        Returns:
1779            Select: the modified expression.
1780        """
1781        return _apply_child_list_builder(
1782            *expressions,
1783            instance=self,
1784            arg="from",
1785            append=append,
1786            copy=copy,
1787            prefix="FROM",
1788            into=From,
1789            dialect=dialect,
1790            **opts,
1791        )
1792
1793    def group_by(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:
1794        """
1795        Set the GROUP BY expression.
1796
1797        Example:
1798            >>> Select().from_("tbl").select("x", "COUNT(1)").group_by("x").sql()
1799            'SELECT x, COUNT(1) FROM tbl GROUP BY x'
1800
1801        Args:
1802            *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
1803                If a `Group` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1804                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be wrapped in a `Group`.
1805                If nothing is passed in then a group by is not applied to the expression
1806            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
1807                Otherwise, this flattens all the `Group` expression into a single expression.
1808            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1809            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1810            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1811
1812        Returns:
1813            Select: the modified expression.
1814        """
1815        if not expressions:
1816            return self if not copy else self.copy()
1817        return _apply_child_list_builder(
1818            *expressions,
1819            instance=self,
1820            arg="group",
1821            append=append,
1822            copy=copy,
1823            prefix="GROUP BY",
1824            into=Group,
1825            dialect=dialect,
1826            **opts,
1827        )
1828
1829    def order_by(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:

2052    def join(
2053        self,
2054        expression,
2055        on=None,
2056        using=None,
2057        append=True,
2058        join_type=None,
2059        join_alias=None,
2060        dialect=None,
2061        copy=True,
2062        **opts,
2063    ) -> Select:
2064        """
2065        Append to or set the JOIN expressions.
2066
2067        Example:
2068            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").join("tbl2", on="tbl1.y = tbl2.y").sql()
2069            'SELECT * FROM tbl JOIN tbl2 ON tbl1.y = tbl2.y'
2070
2071            >>> Select().select("1").from_("a").join("b", using=["x", "y", "z"]).sql()
2072            'SELECT 1 FROM a JOIN b USING (x, y, z)'
2073
2074            Use `join_type` to change the type of join:
2075
2076            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").join("tbl2", on="tbl1.y = tbl2.y", join_type="left outer").sql()
2077            'SELECT * FROM tbl LEFT OUTER JOIN tbl2 ON tbl1.y = tbl2.y'
2078
2079        Args:
2080            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse.
2081                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2082            on (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "on" criteria as a SQL string.
2083                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2084            using (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "using" criteria as a SQL string.
2085                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2086            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
2087                Otherwise, this resets the expressions.
2088            join_type (str): If set, alter the parsed join type
2089            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
2090            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2091            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
2092
2093        Returns:
2094            Select: the modified expression.
2095        """
2096        parse_args = {"dialect": dialect, **opts}
2097
2098        try:
2099            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=Join, prefix="JOIN", **parse_args)
2100        except ParseError:
2101            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=(Join, Expression), **parse_args)
2102
2103        join = expression if isinstance(expression, Join) else Join(this=expression)
2104
2105        if isinstance(join.this, Select):
2106            join.this.replace(join.this.subquery())
2107
2108        if join_type:
2109            natural: t.Optional[Token]
2110            side: t.Optional[Token]
2111            kind: t.Optional[Token]
2112
2113            natural, side, kind = maybe_parse(join_type, into="JOIN_TYPE", **parse_args)  # type: ignore
2114
2115            if natural:
2116                join.set("natural", True)
2117            if side:
2118                join.set("side", side.text)
2119            if kind:
2120                join.set("kind", kind.text)
2121
2122        if on:
2123            on = and_(*ensure_collection(on), dialect=dialect, **opts)
2124            join.set("on", on)
2125
2126        if using:
2127            join = _apply_list_builder(
2128                *ensure_collection(using),
2129                instance=join,
2130                arg="using",
2131                append=append,
2132                copy=copy,
2133                **opts,
2134            )
2135
2136        if join_alias:
2137            join.set("this", alias_(join.this, join_alias, table=True))
2138        return _apply_list_builder(
2139            join,
2140            instance=self,
2141            arg="joins",
2142            append=append,
2143            copy=copy,
2144            **opts,
2145        )
2146

2242    def ctas(self, table, properties=None, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Create:
2243        """
2244        Convert this expression to a CREATE TABLE AS statement.
2245
2246        Example:
2247            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").ctas("x").sql()
2248            'CREATE TABLE x AS SELECT * FROM tbl'
2249
2250        Args:
2251            table (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table name.
2252                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2253            properties (dict): an optional mapping of table properties
2254            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input table.
2255            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2256            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input table.
2257
2258        Returns:
2259            Create: the CREATE TABLE AS expression
2260        """
2261        instance = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
2262        table_expression = maybe_parse(
2263            table,
2264            into=Table,
2265            dialect=dialect,
2266            **opts,
2267        )
2268        properties_expression = None
2269        if properties:
2270            properties_expression = Properties.from_dict(properties)
2271
2272        return Create(
2273            this=table_expression,
2274            kind="table",
2275            expression=instance,
2276            properties=properties_expression,
2277        )

2279    def lock(self, update: bool = True, copy: bool = True) -> Select:
2280        """
2281        Set the locking read mode for this expression.
2282
2283        Examples:
2284            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock().sql("mysql")
2285            "SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR UPDATE"
2286
2287            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock(update=False).sql("mysql")
2288            "SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR SHARE"
2289
2290        Args:
2291            update: if `True`, the locking type will be `FOR UPDATE`, else it will be `FOR SHARE`.
2292            copy: if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2293
2294        Returns:
2295            The modified expression.
2296        """
2297
2298        inst = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
2299        inst.set("lock", Lock(update=update))
2300
2301        return inst

2100        except ParseError:

2110            side: t.Optional[Token]

Returns the first non subquery.

output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name

class Star(Expression): 
2391class Star(Expression):
2392    arg_types = {"except": False, "replace": False}
2393
2394    @property
2395    def name(self):
2396        return "*"
2397
2398    @property
2399    def output_name(self):
2400        return self.name
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

class Alias(Expression): 
2763class Alias(Expression):
2764    arg_types = {"this": True, "alias": False}
2765
2766    @property
2767    def output_name(self):
2768        return self.alias
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

class Func(Condition): 
2833class Func(Condition):
2834    """
2835    The base class for all function expressions.
2836
2837    Attributes:
2838        is_var_len_args (bool): if set to True the last argument defined in arg_types will be
2839            treated as a variable length argument and the argument's value will be stored as a list.
2840        _sql_names (list): determines the SQL name (1st item in the list) and aliases (subsequent items)
2841            for this function expression. These values are used to map this node to a name during parsing
2842            as well as to provide the function's name during SQL string generation. By default the SQL
2843            name is set to the expression's class name transformed to snake case.
2844    """
2845
2846    is_var_len_args = False
2847
2848    @classmethod
2849    def from_arg_list(cls, args):
2850        if cls.is_var_len_args:
2851            all_arg_keys = list(cls.arg_types)
2852            # If this function supports variable length argument treat the last argument as such.
2853            non_var_len_arg_keys = all_arg_keys[:-1] if cls.is_var_len_args else all_arg_keys
2854            num_non_var = len(non_var_len_arg_keys)
2855
2856            args_dict = {arg_key: arg for arg, arg_key in zip(args, non_var_len_arg_keys)}
2857            args_dict[all_arg_keys[-1]] = args[num_non_var:]
2858        else:
2859            args_dict = {arg_key: arg for arg, arg_key in zip(args, cls.arg_types)}
2860
2861        return cls(**args_dict)
2862
2863    @classmethod
2864    def sql_names(cls):
2865        if cls is Func:
2866            raise NotImplementedError(
2867                "SQL name is only supported by concrete function implementations"
2868            )
2869        if "_sql_names" not in cls.__dict__:
2870            cls._sql_names = [camel_to_snake_case(cls.__name__)]
2871        return cls._sql_names
2872
2873    @classmethod
2874    def sql_name(cls):
2875        return cls.sql_names()[0]
2876
2877    @classmethod
2878    def default_parser_mappings(cls):
2879        return {name: cls.from_arg_list for name in cls.sql_names()}

The base class for all function expressions.

Attributes

  • _sql_names (list): determines the SQL name (1st item in the list) and aliases (subsequent items) for this function expression. These values are used to map this node to a name during parsing as well as to provide the function's name during SQL string generation. By default the SQL name is set to the expression's class name transformed to snake case.

class Cast(Func): 
2962class Cast(Func):
2963    arg_types = {"this": True, "to": True}
2964
2965    @property
2966    def name(self):
2967        return self.this.name
2968
2969    @property
2970    def to(self):
2971        return self.args["to"]
2972
2973    @property
2974    def output_name(self):
2975        return self.name
2976
2977    def is_type(self, dtype: DataType.Type) -> bool:
2978        return self.to.is_type(dtype)
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

def maybe_parse( sql_or_expression: 'str | Expression', *, into: Optional[<MagicMock id='4431951808'>] = None, dialect: <MagicMock id='4445786656'> = None, prefix: Optional[str] = None, **opts) -> sqlglot.expressions.Expression: 
3559def maybe_parse(
3560    sql_or_expression: str | Expression,
3561    *,
3562    into: t.Optional[IntoType] = None,
3563    dialect: DialectType = None,
3564    prefix: t.Optional[str] = None,
3565    **opts,
3566) -> Expression:
3567    """Gracefully handle a possible string or expression.
3568
3569    Example:
3570        >>> maybe_parse("1")
3571        (LITERAL this: 1, is_string: False)
3572        >>> maybe_parse(to_identifier("x"))
3573        (IDENTIFIER this: x, quoted: False)
3574
3575    Args:
3576        sql_or_expression: the SQL code string or an expression
3577        into: the SQLGlot Expression to parse into
3578        dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expressions (in the case that an
3579            input expression is a SQL string).
3580        prefix: a string to prefix the sql with before it gets parsed
3581            (automatically includes a space)
3582        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions (again, in the case
3583            that an input expression is a SQL string).
3584
3585    Returns:
3586        Expression: the parsed or given expression.
3587    """
3588    if isinstance(sql_or_expression, Expression):
3589        return sql_or_expression
3590
3591    import sqlglot
3592
3593    sql = str(sql_or_expression)
3594    if prefix:
3595        sql = f"{prefix} {sql}"
3596    return sqlglot.parse_one(sql, read=dialect, into=into, **opts)

Gracefully handle a possible string or expression.

Example
>>> maybe_parse("1")
(LITERAL this: 1, is_string: False)
>>> maybe_parse(to_identifier("x"))
(IDENTIFIER this: x, quoted: False)
Args
  • sql_or_expression: the SQL code string or an expression
  • into: the SQLGlot Expression to parse into
  • dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expressions (in the case that an input expression is a SQL string).
  • prefix: a string to prefix the sql with before it gets parsed (automatically includes a space)
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions (again, in the case that an input expression is a SQL string).
Returns

Expression: the parsed or given expression.

def union(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts): 
3742def union(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
3743    """
3744    Initializes a syntax tree from one UNION expression.
3745
3746    Example:
3747        >>> union("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
3748        'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
3749
3750    Args:
3751        left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side.
3752            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3753        right (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the right-hand side.
3754            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3755        distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
3756        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
3757        opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
3758    Returns:
3759        Union: the syntax tree for the UNION expression.
3760    """
3761    left = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=left, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3762    right = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=right, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3763
3764    return Union(this=left, expression=right, distinct=distinct)

Initializes a syntax tree from one UNION expression.

Example
>>> union("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
Args
  • left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • right (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the right-hand side. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns

Union: the syntax tree for the UNION expression.

def update( table, properties, where=None, from_=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> sqlglot.expressions.Update: 
3861def update(table, properties, where=None, from_=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> Update:
3862    """
3863    Creates an update statement.
3864
3865    Example:
3866        >>> update("my_table", {"x": 1, "y": "2", "z": None}, from_="baz", where="id > 1").sql()
3867        "UPDATE my_table SET x = 1, y = '2', z = NULL FROM baz WHERE id > 1"
3868
3869    Args:
3870        *properties (Dict[str, Any]): dictionary of properties to set which are
3871            auto converted to sql objects eg None -> NULL
3872        where (str): sql conditional parsed into a WHERE statement
3873        from_ (str): sql statement parsed into a FROM statement
3874        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
3875        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
3876
3877    Returns:
3878        Update: the syntax tree for the UPDATE statement.
3879    """
3880    update = Update(this=maybe_parse(table, into=Table, dialect=dialect))
3881    update.set(
3882        "expressions",
3883        [
3884            EQ(this=maybe_parse(k, dialect=dialect, **opts), expression=convert(v))
3885            for k, v in properties.items()
3886        ],
3887    )
3888    if from_:
3889        update.set(
3890            "from",
3891            maybe_parse(from_, into=From, dialect=dialect, prefix="FROM", **opts),
3892        )
3893    if isinstance(where, Condition):
3894        where = Where(this=where)
3895    if where:
3896        update.set(
3897            "where",
3898            maybe_parse(where, into=Where, dialect=dialect, prefix="WHERE", **opts),
3899        )
3900    return update

Creates an update statement.

Example
>>> update("my_table", {"x": 1, "y": "2", "z": None}, from_="baz", where="id > 1").sql()
"UPDATE my_table SET x = 1, y = '2', z = NULL FROM baz WHERE id > 1"
Args
  • *properties (Dict[str, Any]): dictionary of properties to set which are auto converted to sql objects eg None -> NULL
  • where (str): sql conditional parsed into a WHERE statement
  • from_ (str): sql statement parsed into a FROM statement
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.

def delete(table, where=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> sqlglot.expressions.Delete: 
3903def delete(table, where=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> Delete:
3904    """
3905    Builds a delete statement.
3906
3907    Example:
3908        >>> delete("my_table", where="id > 1").sql()

3924    )

def alias_(expression, alias, table=False, dialect=None, quoted=None, **opts): 
4117def alias_(expression, alias, table=False, dialect=None, quoted=None, **opts):
4118    """
4119    Create an Alias expression.
4120    Example:
4121        >>> alias_('foo', 'bar').sql()
4122        'foo AS bar'
4123
4124    Args:
4125        expression (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
4126            If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
4127        alias (str | Identifier): the alias name to use. If the name has
4128            special characters it is quoted.
4129        table (bool): create a table alias, default false
4130        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
4131        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
4132
4133    Returns:
4134        Alias: the aliased expression
4135    """
4136    exp = maybe_parse(expression, dialect=dialect, **opts)
4137    alias = to_identifier(alias, quoted=quoted)
4138
4139    if table:
4140        expression.set("alias", TableAlias(this=alias))
4141        return expression
4142
4143    # We don't set the "alias" arg for Window expressions, because that would add an IDENTIFIER node in
4144    # the AST, representing a "named_window" [1] construct (eg. bigquery). What we want is an ALIAS node
4145    # for the complete Window expression.
4146    #
4147    # [1]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/reference/standard-sql/window-function-calls
4148
4149    if "alias" in exp.arg_types and not isinstance(exp, Window):
4150        exp = exp.copy()
4151        exp.set("alias", alias)
4152        return exp
4153    return Alias(this=exp, alias=alias)

Create an Alias expression.

Example
>>> alias_('foo', 'bar').sql()
'foo AS bar'
Args
  • expression (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse. If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
  • alias (str | Identifier): the alias name to use. If the name has special characters it is quoted.
  • table (bool): create a table alias, default false
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns

Alias: the aliased expression

4232def values(

4238

4240        >>> values([(1, '2')]).sql()

4244        values: values statements that will be converted to SQL
4245        alias: optional alias

4247         If either are provided then an alias is also required.

4249         in order to help with type inference.

4252        Values: the Values expression object
4253    """

4255        raise ValueError("Alias is required when providing columns")

4257        TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias), columns=[to_identifier(x) for x in columns])
4258        if columns
4259        else TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias) if alias else None)
4260    )
4261    expressions = [convert(tup) for tup in values]
4262    if columns and isinstance(columns, dict):
4263        types = list(columns.values())
4264        expressions[0].set(
4265            "expressions",
4266            [cast(x, types[i]) for i, x in enumerate(expressions[0].expressions)],
4267        )
4268    return Values(
4269        expressions=expressions,
4270        alias=table_alias,
4271    )
